honeywell.printer.configuration.ez

Class GeneralConfiguration

  • java.lang.Object
    • honeywell.printer.configuration.ez.PrinterData
      • honeywell.printer.configuration.ez.PrinterState
        • honeywell.printer.configuration.ez.GeneralConfiguration
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable

    public class GeneralConfiguration
extends PrinterState
    This class handles the data from an {CF?} query as well as accessors to read the data values.

    This class supports the following possible parameters:

    ParameterDescription
    AWhite Space Advance Configuration
    BSerial Baud Rate
    DPrinting Darkness Adjustment
    FForm Feed Enabled
    GBeep When Charger Connected
    HHandshake type
    ILines Per Page
    JJob Status Report
    LDefault Printing Protocol
    LTSelf Test Print Language
    MForm Feed Centering
    NData Bits
    PSerial Communication Parity
    PFFormfeed Button Disabled
    POPower Button Disabled
    PRRF Button Disabled
    QCNumber of times to add .25 volts or 0x19 to the QMark volt threshold. The default is 0 and as this number increases the QMark is more difficult to detect, as it decreases the QMark is easier to detect.
    RRF Power Timeout
    SSound Enabled
    TSystem Timeout
    TPSpecial Test Print Mode
    UPaper Out Beep
    UCWhat USB device class is the printer currently configured for.
    USBIs USB the current communication method.
    DSDeep Sleep
    See Also:
    Serialized Form

    • Constructor Detail

      • GeneralConfiguration

        public GeneralConfiguration(ConnectionBase connection)
        The default constructor will initialize the class with default values.

        Initially all of the _IsValid parameters will be false because no data has been processed. To 'populate' the values, the object must invoke @see PrinterState.queryPrinter(int) with the query response string.

        Parameters:
        connection - connection to printer

      • getQStopMultiplier

        public long getQStopMultiplier()
        Number of times to add .25 volts or 0x19 to the QMark volt threshold. The default is 0 and as this number increases the QMark is more difficult to detect, as it decreases the QMark is easier to detect.

        The return value for this parameter is only valid if getQStopMultiplier_IsPresent() returns true. Because of differences in configuration, hardware or version certain parameter may not exist and the results returned may not be valid.

        Returns:
        The current value for the parameter.
        See Also:
        getQStopMultiplier_IsPresent()
